d by voices in both Britain and the empire, and how it influenced later imperial developments such as the immigration to Britain of ‘imperial citizens’ from the colonies after the Second World War. A work of political, intellectual and cultural history, the book re-incorporates the histories of the settlement colonies into imperial history, and suggests the importance of comparative history in understanding the imperial endeavour. It will be of interest to students of imperialism, British political and intellectual history, and of the various former dominions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCitizenshipxHistory. 0aCitizenship. 0aImperialismxHistory. 0aImperialism. 0aNationalismxHistory. 0aNationalism. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aBoer War.  aBritish imperialism.  aGreat War.  aearly twentieth century.  aempire.  aimperial citizenship.  aimperial subjects.  anation-state.  anational identity.  asettlement colonies.1 aGorman, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779142940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847791429423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847791429/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles